39 PART II. IMPLICIT BIAS IN HEALTH CARE
40 SECTION 2.1.(a) Part 5 of Article 1B of Chapter 130A of the General Statutes is
41 amended by adding two new sections to read:
42 "§ 130A-33.62. Department to establish implicit bias training program for health care
43 professionals engaged in perinatal care.
44 (a) The following definitions apply in this section:
45 (1) Health care professional. – A licensed physician or other health care provider
46 licensed, registered, accredited, or certified to perform perinatal care and
47 regulated under the authority of a health care professional licensing authority.
48 (2) Health care professional licensing authority. – The Department of Health and
49 Human Services or an agency, board, council, or committee with the authority
50 to impose training or education requirements or licensure fees as a condition
51 of practicing in this State as a health care professional.
Page 4 House Bill 725-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (3) Implicit bias. – A bias in judgment or behavior that results from subtle
2 cognitive processes, including implicit prejudice and implicit stereotypes, that
3 often operate at a level below conscious awareness and without intentional
4 control.
5 (4) Implicit prejudice. – Prejudicial negative feelings or beliefs about a group that
6 a person holds without being aware of them.
7 (5) Implicit stereotypes. – The unconscious attributions of particular qualities to
8 a member of a certain social group that are influenced by experience and based
9 on learned associations between various qualities and social categories,
10 including race and gender.
11 (6) Perinatal care. – The provision of care during pregnancy, labor, delivery, and
12 postpartum and neonatal periods.
13 (7) Perinatal facility. – A hospital, clinic, or birthing center that provides perinatal
14 care in this State.
15 (b) The Department, in collaboration with (i) community-based organizations led by
16 black women that serve primarily black birthing people and (ii) a historically black college or
17 university or other institution that primarily serves minority populations, shall create or identify
18 an evidence-based implicit bias training program for health care professionals involved in
19 perinatal care. The implicit bias training program shall include, at a minimum, all of the following
20 components:
21 (1) Identification of previous or current unconscious biases and misinformation.
22 (2) Identification of personal, interpersonal, institutional, structural, and cultural
23 barriers to inclusion.
24 (3) Corrective measures to decrease implicit bias at the interpersonal and
25 institutional levels, including ongoing policies and practices for that purpose.
26 (4) Information about the effects of implicit bias, including, but not limited to,
27 ongoing personal effects of racism and the historical and contemporary
28 exclusion and oppression of minority communities.
29 (5) Information about cultural identity across racial or ethnic groups.
30 (6) Information about how to communicate more effectively across identities,
31 including racial, ethnic, religious, and gender identities.
32 (7) Information about power dynamics and organizational decision making.
33 (8) Trauma-informed care best practices and an emphasis on shared decision
34 making between providers and patients.
35 (9) Information about health inequities within the perinatal care field, including
36 information on how implicit bias impacts maternal and infant health
37 outcomes.
38 (10) Perspectives of diverse, local constituency groups and experts on particular
39 racial, identity, cultural, and provider-community relations issues in the
40 community.
41 (11) Information about socioeconomic bias.
42 (12) Information about reproductive justice.
43 (c) Notwithstanding any provision of Chapter 90 or Chapter 93B of the General Statutes,
44 or any other provision of law to the contrary, all health care professionals are required to complete
45 the implicit bias training program established under this section as follows:
46 (1) Health care professionals who hold a current license, registration,
47 accreditation, or certification on December 31, 2025, shall complete the
48 training program no later than December 31, 2026.
49 (2) Health care professionals issued an initial license, registration, accreditation,
50 or certification on or after January 1, 2026, shall complete the training
51 program no later than one year after the date of issuance.
House Bill 725-First Edition Page 5

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 A health care professional licensing authority shall not renew the license, registration,
2 accreditation, or certification of a health care professional unless the health care professional
3 provides proof of completion of the training program established under this section within the
4 24-month period leading up to the date of the renewal application.
5 (d) The Department is encouraged to seek opportunities to make the implicit bias training
6 program established under this section available to all health care professionals and to promote
7 its use among the following groups:
8 (1) All maternity care providers and any employees who interact with pregnant
9 and postpartum individuals in the provider setting, including front desk
10 employees, sonographers, schedulers, health system-employed lactation
11 consultants, hospital or health system administrators, security staff, and other
12 employees.
13 (2) Undergraduate programs that funnel into health professions schools.
14 (3) Providers of the special supplemental nutrition program for women, infants,
15 and children under section 17 of the Child Nutrition Act of 1966.
16 (4) Obstetric emergency simulation trainings or related trainings.
17 (5) Emergency department employees, emergency medical technicians, and other
18 specialized health care providers who interact with pregnant and postpartum
19 individuals.
20 (e) The Department shall collect the following information for the purpose of informing
21 ongoing improvements to the implicit bias training program:
22 (1) Data on the causes of maternal mortality.
23 (2) Rates of maternal mortality, including rates distinguished by age, race,
24 ethnicity, socioeconomic status, and geographic location within this State.
25 (3) Other factors the Department deems relevant for assessing and improving the
26 implicit bias training program.
27 "§ 130A-33.63. Rights of perinatal care patients.
28 (a) A patient receiving care at a perinatal care facility, defined as a hospital, clinic, or
29 birthing center that provides perinatal care in this State, has the following rights:
30 (1) To be informed of continuing health care requirements following discharge.
31 (2) To be informed that, if the patient so authorizes, and to the extent permitted
32 by law, the hospital or health care facility may provide to a friend or family
33 member information about the patient's continuing health care requirements
34 following discharge.
35 (3) To actively participate in decisions regarding the patient's medical care and
36 the right to refuse treatment.
37 (4) To receive appropriate pain assessment and treatment.
38 (5) To receive care and treatment free from discrimination on the basis of age,
39 race, ethnicity, color, religion, ancestry, disability, medical condition, genetic
40 information, marital status, sex, gender identity, gender expression, sexual
41 orientation, socioeconomic status, citizenship, nationality, immigration status,
42 primary language, or language proficiency.
43 (6) To receive information on how to file a complaint with the Division of Health
44 Service Regulation or the Human Rights Commission or both about any
45 violation of these rights.
46 (b) Each perinatal care facility shall provide to each perinatal care patient upon admission
47 to the facility, or as soon as reasonably practical following admission to the facility, a written
48 copy of the rights enumerated in subsection (a) of this section. The facility may provide this
49 information to the patient by electronic means, and it may be provided with other notices
50 regarding patient rights."
