9 PART III. SUPPORTING AND DIVERSIFYING LACTATION CONSULTANT
10 TRAINING PROGRAMS
11 SECTION 3.1.(a) The following definitions apply in this section:
12 (1) Historically Black Colleges and Universities or HBCUs. – Institutions of
13 higher education that were founded to educate black citizens who were
14 historically restricted from attending predominantly white institutions of
15 higher education.
16 (2) Lactation consultants. – Educators or counselors trained in breast feeding or
17 chest feeding practices, lactation care, and lactation services.
18 (3) Lactation services. – The clinical application of scientific principles and a
19 multidisciplinary body of evidence for evaluation, problem identification,
20 treatment, education, and consultation to childbearing families regarding
21 lactation care and services.
22 (4) Maternity care services. – Health care related to an individual's pregnancy,
23 childbirth, or postpartum recovery.
24 (5) Preceptor. – A person who is a certified lactation consultant and meets the
25 requirements of the International Board of Lactation Consultant Examiners to
26 supervise lactation consultants-in-training during the training period.
27 SECTION 3.1.(b) There is appropriated from the General Fund to the Board of
28 Governors of The University of North Carolina the sum of three million dollars ($3,000,000) in
29 nonrecurring funds for each year of the 2025-2027 fiscal biennium for the purposes of recruiting,
30 training, and retaining a diverse workforce of lactation consultants in North Carolina by
31 supporting the infrastructure and sustainability of lactation consultant training programs at
32 Historically Black Colleges and Universities located within the State. These funds shall be
33 distributed equally among Bennett College, Fayetteville State University, Johnson C. Smith
34 University, North Carolina Agricultural & Technical State University, and North Carolina
35 Central University to cover costs incurred by each university for administering a lactation
36 training program, including, but not limited to:
37 (1) Leasing or other costs for teaching facilities or approved clinical training sites.
38 (2) Student aid or scholarships.
39 (3) Compensation for lactation consultant training program teachers and
40 preceptors.
41 SECTION 3.1.(c) The Department of Health and Human Services shall provide
42 technical assistance to Bennett College, Fayetteville State University, Johnson C. Smith
43 University, North Carolina Agricultural & Technical State University, and North Carolina
44 Central University with respect to the following:
45 (1) Developing culturally appropriate training content for the lactation consultant
46 training programs funded by State appropriations.
47 (2) Recruiting persons from historically marginalized populations to enroll in the
48 lactation consultant training programs offered at these universities.
49 (3) Recruiting historically underutilized providers to serve as teachers and
50 preceptors in the lactation consultant training programs offered at these
51 universities.
House Bill 725-First Edition Page 7

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (4) Identifying rural and medically underserved areas of the State experiencing a
2 shortage of lactation consultants in order to recruit program graduates to work
3 in these areas.
4 SECTION 3.1.(d) By May 1, 2028, the Department of Health and Human Services
5 shall evaluate and submit a report to the Joint Legislative Oversight Committee on Health and
6 Human Services and the Joint Legislative Education Oversight Committee on the benefits
7 received by the State as a result of funding the lactation consultant training programs at North
8 Carolina Agricultural & Technical State University and Johnson C. Smith University. The report
9 shall include at least all of the following information and recommendations:
10 (1) The total number of lactation consultants who received training at one of the
11 State-funded HBCU lactation programs, broken down by (i) race and ethnicity
12 and (ii) chosen work site, such as hospital, provider office, or
13 community-based organization.
14 (2) A review of the prenatal and postpartum experiences of patients who received
15 lactation consultant services from a health care professional who graduated
16 from one of the State-funded HBCU lactation consultant programs. The
17 review shall address patients' experiences relative to the following:
18 a. Health insurance coverage for maternity care services, including
19 telehealth lactation consultant services.
20 b. Contributing factors to population-based disparities in breast feeding
21 and chest feeding outcomes, including bias and discrimination toward
22 patients who are members of racial and ethnic minority groups.
23 c. Patient satisfaction with the services received from these lactation
24 consultants.
25 d. Breast feeding or chest feeding initiation and duration rates of patients
26 who received services from these lactation consultants.
27 SECTION 3.2. This Part becomes effective July 1, 2025.
